  Architectural Alignment & Implementation Brief

 1. Core Architecture Clarification (Read Carefully)
There is minor confusion regarding the role of the backend and OpenRouter. 
* **OpenRouter is NOT the backend framework.** OpenRouter is strictly used as our cloud-hosted API gateway to run **Gemma 4**, removing the need for users to download models locally.
* **The PWA is Client-First / Serverless-Ready.** The execution logic lives in `client.js`. The `.env` keys are utilized to authenticate these calls. Do NOT restructure the backend or alter the current OpenRouter API key routing until the core application is functional.

---

 2. Target Implementation: Client-Side SkillChains
We are keeping the orchestration entirely within `client.js`. Instead of sending one massive prompt, `client.js` will execute a linear sequence of distinct model skills to guarantee high-quality code generation.

** ** ** SkillChain Execution Flow in `client.js`
```javascript
// client.js - Orchestrator
async function generateVibeUI(userPrompt) {
  try {
    showLoadingStatus("Architecting application state...");
    // Skill 1: Extract state data structure
    const stateBlueprint = await callOpenRouter(userPrompt, systemPrompts.architect);

    showLoadingStatus("Designing Tailwind layout...");
    // Skill 2: Generate structural HTML/CSS using the state blueprint
    const uiShell = await callOpenRouter(
      `User intent: ${userPrompt}. Structure your elements around this data schema: ${stateBlueprint}`, 
      systemPrompts.styler
    );

    showLoadingStatus("Injecting interactive logic...");
    // Skill 3: Inject Vanilla JS interactivity and bind to state
    const completeApp = await callOpenRouter(
      `Add dynamic script handling to this HTML layout: ${uiShell}. Use this state data: ${stateBlueprint}`,
      systemPrompts.engineer
    );

    // Final step: Inject telemetry and render to the Virtual File System
    const runtimeApp = injectTelemetry(completeApp);
    renderToSandboxIframe(runtimeApp);
    
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("SkillChain broken:", error);
  }
}

